\begin{exercise}
\textit{Solución} \\
\begin{enumerate}
\item Equilibrio de Nash en el mercado downstream. \\

Función de mejor respuesta de la firma D1:
$$\Pi^D_1 = \Big( p_1 - c_1 \Big) q_1 = \Big( p_1 - w_i - 15 \Big) \Big( 100 - p_1 + \frac{p_2}{2} \Big)$$
$$\frac{\partial \Pi^D_1}{\partial p_1} = \Big( 100 - p_1 + \frac{p_2}{2} \Big) + \Big( p_1 - w_i - 15 \Big) (-1) = 0 \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow 100 - p_1 + \frac{p_2}{2} - p_1 + w_i + 15 = 0 \Rightarrow 115 + \frac{p_2}{2} + w_i = 2p_1 \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{R_1(p_2): p_1 = 57.5 + \frac{w_i}{2} + \frac{p_2}{4}}$$

Función de mejor respuesta de la firma D2:
$$\Pi^D_2 = \Big( p_2 - c_2 \Big) q_2 = \Big( p_2 - w_i - 15 \Big) \Big( 100 - p_2 + \frac{p_1}{2} \Big)$$
$$\frac{\partial \Pi^D_2}{\partial p_2} = \Big( 100 - p_2 + \frac{p_1}{2} \Big) + \Big( p_2 - w_i - 15 \Big) (-1) = 0 \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow 100 - p_2 + \frac{p_1}{2} - p_2 + w_i + 15 = 0 \Rightarrow 115 + \frac{p_1}{2} + w_i = 2p_2 \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{R_2(p_1): p_2 = 57.5 + \frac{w_i}{2} + \frac{p_1}{4}}$$

Intersectando ambas FMR obtenemos:
$$p_1^* = 57.5 + \frac{w_i}{2} + \frac{1}{4} \Big( 57.5 + \frac{w_i}{2} + \frac{p_1^*}{4} \Big) = 71.875 + \frac{5}{8} \, w_i + \frac{p_1^*}{16} \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \frac{15}{16} \, p_1^* = 71.875 + \frac{5}{8} \, w_i \Rightarrow p_1^* = \frac{16}{15} \Big( 71.875 + \frac{5}{8} \, w_i \Big) \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{p_1^* = \frac{230}{3} + \frac{2}{3} \, w_i}$$

Resolviendo $R_2(p_1^*)$ obtenemos que:
$$\color{blue}\boxed{p_2^* = \frac{230}{3} + \frac{2}{3} \, w_i}$$

\newpage

Evaluando en las funciones de demanda de cada uno de los respectivos mercados, obtenemos:
$$q_1^*(p_1^*;p_2^*) = 100 - p_1^* + \frac{p_2^*}{2} = 100 - \left( \frac{230}{3} + \frac{2}{3} \, w_i \right) + \frac{1}{2} \left( \frac{230}{3} + \frac{2}{3} \, w_i \right) = $$
$$= 100 - \frac{230}{3} - \frac{2}{3} \, w_i  + \frac{230}{6} + \frac{2}{6} \, w_i \Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{q_1^* = \frac{185 - w_i}{3}}$$

$$q_2^*(p_1^*;p_2^*) = 100 - p_2^* + \frac{p_1^*}{2} = 100 - \left( \frac{230}{3} + \frac{2}{3} \, w_i \right) + \frac{1}{2} \left( \frac{230}{3} + \frac{2}{3} \, w_i \right) = $$
$$= 100 - \frac{230}{3} - \frac{2}{3} \, w_i  + \frac{230}{6} + \frac{2}{6} \, w_i \Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{q_2^* = \frac{185 - w_i}{3}}$$

Los beneficios de equilibrio serán:
$$\Pi_1^D = \left( \frac{230 + 2w_i}{3} - w_i - 15 \right) \left( \frac{185-w_i}{3} \right) = \left( \frac{230+2w_i-3w_i-45}{3} \right) \left( \frac{185-w_i}{3} \right) \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{\Pi_1^D = \left( \frac{185-w_i}{3}\right)^2}$$

$$\Pi_2^D = \left( \frac{230 + 2w_i}{3} - w_i - 15 \right) \left( \frac{185-w_i}{3} \right) = \left( \frac{230+2w_i-3w_i-45}{3} \right) \left( \frac{185-w_i}{3} \right) \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{\Pi_2^D = \left( \frac{185-w_i}{3}\right)^2}$$

\item Si las empresas upstream compiten en precios, entonces:
$$P^U = MC_j^U \Rightarrow w_j = MC_j^U \Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{w_j = 10}$$

Por lo tanto:
$$\color{blue}\boxed{q_1^* = q_2^* = \frac{175}{3}}$$
$$\color{blue}\boxed{p_1^* = p_2^* = \frac{250}{3}}$$
$$\color{blue}\boxed{\Pi_1^U = \Pi_2^U = 0}$$
$$\color{blue}\boxed{\Pi_1^D = \Pi_2^D = \left( \frac{175}{3} \right)^2 }$$

\item Demanda derivada por U2 luego de la fusión. \\

Función de mejor respusta de la firma fusionada U1-D1:
$$\Pi_1 = \Big( p_1 - c_1 \Big) q_1(p_1;p_2) = \Big( p_1 - 25 \Big) \Big( 100 - p_1 + \frac{p_2}{2} \Big)$$
$$\frac{\partial \Pi_1}{\partial p_1} = \Big( 100 - p_1 + \frac{p_2}{2} \Big) + \Big( p_1 - 25 \Big) (-1) = 0 \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{R_1(p_2):p_1 = \frac{125 + 0.5p_2}{2}}$$

Función de mejor respuesta de la empresa D2:
$$\Pi^D_2 = \Big( p_2 - c_2 \Big) q_2 = \Big( p_2 - w_2 - 15 \Big) \Big( 100 - p_2 + \frac{p_1}{2} \Big)$$
$$\frac{\partial \Pi^D_2}{\partial p_2} = \Big( 100 - p_2 + \frac{p_1}{2} \Big) + \Big( p_2 - w_2 - 15 \Big) (-1) = 0 \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow 100 - p_2 + \frac{p_1}{2} - p_2 + w_2 + 15 = 0 \Rightarrow 115 + \frac{p_1}{2} + w_2 = 2p_2 \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{R_2(p_1): p_2 = 57.5 + \frac{w_2}{2} + \frac{p_1}{4}}$$

Intersectando ambas FMR obtenemos:
$$p_1^* = 62.5 + \frac{1}{4} \left( 57.5 + \frac{w_2}{2} + \frac{p_1^*}{4} \right) = 76.875 + \frac{w_2}{8} + \frac{p_1^*}{16} \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \frac{15}{16} \, p_1^* = 76.875 + \frac{w_2}{8} \Rightarrow p_1^* = \frac{16}{15} \left( 76.875 + \frac{w_2}{8} \right) \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{p_1^* = 82 + \frac{2}{15} \, w_2}$$

$$p_2^* = 57.5 + \frac{w_2}{2} + \frac{1}{4} \left( 82 + \frac{2}{15} \, w_2\right) = 57.5 + \frac{w_2}{2} + 20.5 + \frac{w_2}{30} \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{p_2^* = 78 + \frac{8}{15} \, w_2}$$

Evaluando ambos precios en la demanda que enfrenta D2 podemos obtener la demanda derivada que enfrenta U2:
$$q_2^D(p_1^*;p_2^*) = 100 - \left( 78 + \frac{8}{15} \, w_2 \right) + \frac{1}{2} \left( 82 + \frac{2}{15} \, w_2 \right) = 100 - 78 - \frac{8}{15} \, w_2 + 41 + \frac{1}{15} \, w_2 \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{q_2^U(w_2) = 63 - \frac{7}{15} \, w_2}$$

\item U2 quedó como firma monopólica en el mercado upstream, vendiendole a D2 en el mercado downstream. \\

Comenzamos hallando la demanda derivada inversa que enfrenta U2:
$$q_2^U(w_2) = 63 - \frac{7}{15} \, w_2 \Rightarrow \frac{7}{15} \, w_2 = 63 - q_2^U \Rightarrow \frac{15}{7} \Big( 63 - q_2^U \Big) \Rightarrow$$
$$\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{w_2(q_2^U) = 135 - \frac{15}{7} \, q_2^U}$$

U2 igual ingreso marginal a costo marginal:
$$MR^U_2 = MC^U_2 \Rightarrow 135 - \frac{30}{7} \, q_2^U = 10 \Rightarrow 125 = \frac{30}{7} \, q_2^U \Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{q_2^{U^*} = \frac{175}{6}} \color{black}\Rightarrow \color{blue}\boxed{w_2^* = \frac{145}{2}}$$ 

